1 (a) "Accelerated learning" means an organized way of helping students meet
2 individual academic goals by providing direct instruction to eliminate student
3 performance deficiencies or enable students to move more quickly through
4 course requirements and pursue higher level skill development;
5 (b) "Advanced coursework" means educational programs or opportunities
6 designed to challenge students with more rigorous content beyond the
7 standard curriculum, including but not limited to advanced placement,
8 International Baccalaureate, and honors courses;
9 (c) "Constructed-response items" or "performance-based items" means individual
10 test items that require the student to create an answer rather than select a
11 response and may include fill-in-the-blank, short-answer, extended-answer,
12 open-response, and writing-on-demand formats;
13 (d) "Criterion-referenced test" means a test that is aligned with defined academic
14 content standards and measures an individual student's level of performance
15 against the standards;
16 (e) "Formative assessment" means a process used by teachers and students during
17 instruction to adjust ongoing teaching and learning to improve students'
18 achievement of intended instructional outcomes. Formative assessments may
19 include the use of commercial assessments, curriculum-embedded
20 assessments, classroom observations, teacher-designed [classroom tests and
21 ]assessments, and other processes and assignments to gain information about
22 individual student learning that reflects developmentally appropriate grade-
23 level performance;
24 (f) "Interim assessments" means assessments that are given periodically
25 throughout the year to provide diagnostic information and to show individual
26 student performance against content standards;
27 (g) "Summative assessment" means an assessment given at the end of the school
