Page 36 of 45
HB025720.100 - 1141 - XXXX 4/1/2026 10:41 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 257/EN
1 certification, licensure, or credential as identified by the Kentucky Workforce
2 Innovation Board pursuant to KRS 158.6455(1)(d)[(e)] or passing an end-of-
3 program assessment for articulated postsecondary credit as designated by the
4 Kentucky Department of Education Office of Career and Technical
5 Education;
6 (m) "Weighted high-cost full-time equivalents" means the total number of
7 secondary students enrolled in high-cost career and technical education
8 programs, multiplied by the number of credit hours in which those students
9 are enrolled, divided by six (6) hours, and multiplied by one and one-half
10 (1.5); and
11 (n) "Work-based learning program" means a cooperative education program,
12 internship, or registered apprenticeship within the student's chosen approved
13 career and technical education pathway.
14 (2) The Kentucky Department of Education shall provide funds from the department's
15 annual general fund appropriation to support the administrative operations costs of
16 state-operated area technology centers and converted career and technical education
17 centers.
18 (3) For converted career and technical education centers, beginning with fiscal year
19 2024-2025, the Kentucky Department of Education shall deduct from funds
20 designated for the state-operated area technology centers an amount equal to the
21 administrative operations costs of each converted career and technical education
22 center in the amount received by the center in the most recent fiscal year that the
23 center was under state management and control. The funds for each converted
24 career and technical education center shall be divided as follows:
25 (a) Seventy-five percent (75%) of the funds shall be sent to the local district that
26 has assumed management and control of the center; and
27 (b) Twenty-five percent (25%) of the funds shall be sent to the career and
Page 37 of 45
HB025720.100 - 1141 - XXXX 4/1/2026 10:41 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 257/EN
1 technical education innovation and support fund established in subsection (4)
2 of this section.
3 (4) (a) There is hereby established in the State Treasury a restricted fund to be known
4 as the career and technical education innovation and support fund to receive
5 the funds allocated under subsection (3)(b) of this section. The fund shall
6 consist of moneys received from state appropriations, gifts, grants, and federal
7 funds. The fund shall be administered by the Office of Career and Technical
8 Education. Amounts deposited in the fund shall be used for:
9 1. Supporting innovation in new or emerging career fields;
10 2. Supporting state-operated area technology centers that may experience
11 hardship or natural disasters;
12 3. Personnel costs to provide technical assistance to local districts
13 providing locally operated career and technical education, including
14 technical assistance relating to the monitoring and oversight on the use
15 of supplemental career and technical education funding; and
16 4. Any other purposes reasonably related to improving student outcomes in
17 career and technical education.
18 (b) Notwithstanding KRS 45.229, fund amounts not expended at the close of a
19 fiscal year shall not lapse but shall be carried forward into the next fiscal year.
20 (5) Beginning with the 2024-2025 fiscal year and for each fiscal year thereafter, the
21 Kentucky Department of Education shall distribute to local districts providing
22 locally operated career and technical education and to state-operated area
23 technology centers all general funds designated as supplemental funds to career and
24 technical education programs, subject to the following:
25 (a) A local district providing locally operated career and technical education or a
26 state-operated area technology center shall maintain eligibility for receipt of
27 federal funding pursuant to the Strengthening Career and Technical Education
Page 38 of 45
HB025720.100 - 1141 - XXXX 4/1/2026 10:41 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 257/EN
1 for the 21st Century Act, Pub. L. No. 115-224, to be eligible to receive
2 supplemental funding pursuant to this subsection;
3 (b) All supplemental funds distributed pursuant to this subsection shall be used to
4 improve student outcomes in career and technical education pathways for
5 students in grades nine (9) through twelve (12), including but not limited to
6 student supplies, resources, materials, and equipment that is designed for
7 enhanced quality of instruction in a career and technical education pathway,
8 the purchase and maintenance of industry standard equipment, assisting
9 students with achieving technical skill attainment, and supporting career and
10 technical student organization participation;
11 (c) 1. Supplemental funds for career and technical education shall be divided
12 and allocated to each local district providing locally operated career and
13 technical education and to each state-operated area technology center,
14 with sixty percent (60%) dedicated for enrollment-based funding and
15 forty percent (40%) for incentive-based funding.
16 2. The sixty percent (60%) enrollment-based funding shall be based on a
17 statewide full-time equivalent calculation of the total weighted high-cost
18 full-time equivalents and general-cost full-time equivalents during the
19 prior school year, subject to the following:
20 a. The department shall then distribute the enrollment-based funds
21 for each state-operated area technology center or local district
22 providing locally operated career and technical education based on
23 the center's or district's proportional share of the combined
24 weighted high-cost full-time equivalents and general-cost full-time
25 equivalents of the prior year;
26 b. The department shall distribute the state-operated area technology
27 center fund portion to the respective state-operated area
Page 39 of 45
HB025720.100 - 1141 - XXXX 4/1/2026 10:41 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 257/EN
1 technology centers and the local district fund portion to the
2 respective local districts; and
3 c. The department shall classify qualifying programs as either a high-
4 cost career and technical education program or a general-cost
5 career and technical education program.
6 3. The forty percent (40%) incentives-based funding shall be based on an
7 annual statewide calculation of the total number of qualifying student
8 incentives. The calculation shall only use students that are in grade
9 twelve (12) and use the total incentives earned by those students during
10 secondary education at a state-operated area technology center or within
11 a local district. Once a student has been included in a year's calculation,
12 that student shall not be included in any subsequent year's calculation,
13 subject to the following:
14 a. Qualifying student incentives for students in their grade twelve
15 (12) year shall include:
16 i. Reaching the designation of a concentrator;
17 ii. Technical skill attainment;
18 iii. Completing a required number of hours or achieving a
19 benchmark within a work-based learning program; and
20 iv. Earning an approved career and technical education dual
21 credit;
22 b. The incentives in subdivision a. of this subparagraph shall be
23 allotted to the state-operated area technology center or local
24 district in which it was earned. Each type of incentive shall only be
25 counted once per student at state-operated area technology centers
26 and once per student at local districts for a maximum of four (4)
27 incentives per student at state-operated area technology centers
