6 Section 7. No later than November 1, 2026, the Kentucky Department of
7 Education shall submit a study report to the Legislative Research Commission for referral
8 to the Interim Joint Committee on Education on middle school mathematics and
9 advanced mathematics coursework opportunities. At a minimum, the report shall address:
10 (1) Existing local policies and procedures governing student assignment to
11 advanced mathematics coursework in general and advanced middle school mathematics
12 coursework specifically;
13 (2) The current availability of advanced mathematics coursework in Kentucky
14 public middle schools, identifying the following for public middle schools that offer
15 advanced mathematics coursework:
16 (a) Eligibility criteria for students to be identified for participation in the
17 advanced mathematics coursework;
18 (b) Methods for how students are being identified for participation in the
19 advanced mathematics coursework;
20 (c) For each school district, the number and percentage of students participating
21 in advanced mathematics coursework opportunities by grade level;
22 (d) For each school district, the number and percentage of students who complete
23 advanced middle school mathematics coursework and enroll in Algebra I by grade 8;
24 (e) The defined sequence of advanced mathematics coursework offered in grades
25 6 to 8 and the means of delivering those offerings to students, including whether the
26 course is:
27 1. Offered virtually, in person, or both;
Page 43 of 45
HB025720.100 - 1141 - XXXX 4/1/2026 10:41 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 257/EN
1 2. Offered exclusively to middle school students or in a combined setting with
2 middle and high school students; and
3 3. Taught by a teacher whose primary course load is middle school students or
4 taught by a teacher whose primary course load is high school students;
5 (f) Whether any advanced mathematics coursework previously offered is no
6 longer available to students and the reason for no longer offering that coursework;
7 (g) How the school districts are providing appropriate staffing to support offering
8 access to advanced mathematics coursework; and
9 (h) Barriers the school districts encountered in providing advanced mathematics
10 coursework opportunities, and strategies for overcoming these barriers;
11 (3) A list of each middle school that does not offer advanced mathematics
12 coursework to students that identifies:
13 (a) The accelerated learning opportunities to which middle school students in
14 each identified school are offered access;
15 (b) The specific staffing and facility needs for each identified school to transition
16 to offering access to advanced mathematics coursework;
17 (c) Any scheduling constraints reported by each identified school as a barrier to
18 offering access to advanced mathematics coursework;
19 (d) Other barriers identified by school districts to offering middle school students
20 enrolled in each identified school access to advanced mathematics coursework; and
21 (e) If the middle school historically offered advanced mathematics coursework,
22 the specific reasons the school no longer offers that coursework;
23 (4) The recent rates of participation in advanced mathematics courses of middle
24 school students, identifying the number and percentage of students in each school
25 district's current grade 9, grade 10, grade 11, and grade 12 cohorts that successfully
26 completed designated advanced coursework in middle school;
27 (5) Best-practice strategies for ensuring that students are academically prepared
Page 44 of 45
HB025720.100 - 1141 - XXXX 4/1/2026 10:41 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 257/EN
1 for advanced middle school mathematics coursework, including identification of
2 advanced coursework opportunities or other academic enrichment opportunities that best
3 prepare students for Algebra I coursework by grade 8;
4 (6) Analysis of school district capacity and needs to implement a policy providing
5 all public school students in Kentucky with access to Algebra I coursework by grade 8,
6 including but not limited to:
7 (a) The availability of qualified teachers and staff to support implementation of
8 the policy across each region of the Commonwealth;
9 (b) The scheduling constraints reported by each district;
10 (c) Course selection availability in each district and projected enrollment caps;
11 and
12 (d) Facility, technology, and distance-learning capacity of each district;
13 (7) An analysis of any curriculum gaps between advanced mathematics
14 coursework and grade-level mathematics standards for the courses in which the student
15 would otherwise be enrolled and strategies to ensure that advanced mathematics students
16 master those grade-level standards; and
17 (8) Legislative recommendations to promote and encourage advanced
18 mathematics coursework for middle school students, including but not limited to
19 recommended strategies for:
20 (a) Automatic enrollment in advanced middle school mathematics coursework;
21 (b) Identifying middle school students to participate in advance mathematics
22 coursework; and
23 (c) Small, medium, and large school districts to implement advanced
24 mathematics coursework.
